<BlogPost
  title="Why a Native App"
  description="You could use a browser tab. Here's why a dedicated app is better for the things you use every day."
  date="2026-04-15"
>

  <p>
    You could manage your notes and tasks in a browser tab. Plenty of people do. But there's a reason the tools people reach for most — the ones that become muscle memory — tend to be native apps, not websites.
  </p>

  <h2>It's always there</h2>

  <p>
    Pikos lives in your dock, not in a browser tab buried behind twelve others. Switch to it with Cmd+Tab. It's open in under a second. There's no login screen, no loading spinner, no "reconnecting..." banner. You open it, you're in, you're working.
  </p>

  <h2>It works offline</h2>

  <p>
    No Wi-Fi on the train? No problem. Everything runs on your machine. Write notes, check off tasks, reschedule your afternoon — it all works the same whether you're connected or not. When you're back online, nothing needs to sync because nothing left your device in the first place.
  </p>

  <h2>Keyboard shortcuts that actually work</h2>

  <p>
    Web apps fight the browser for keyboard shortcuts. Cmd+K opens the browser's address bar, not the app's search. Cmd+N opens a new browser window, not a new page. Native apps own the keyboard. Every shortcut in Pikos does what you'd expect, every time, without conflicting with the browser.
  </p>

  <h2>No tab clutter</h2>

  <p>
    Your browser already has too many tabs. Your productivity tool shouldn't be one of them, competing for attention with email, social media, and that article you've been meaning to read. A separate app stays focused because it's separate.
  </p>

  <h2>Fast because it can be</h2>

  <p>
    Web apps download their code every time you visit. They render in a shared browser process alongside everything else you have open. Native apps load once, run in their own process, and can use your hardware directly. The difference shows up as the feeling that everything responds the instant you touch it.
  </p>

  <h2>Not against the web</h2>

  <p>
    Web apps are great for collaboration, for things you share, for tools you use occasionally. But for a personal tool you open twenty times a day — your notes, your tasks, your calendar — a native app is the right shape. It should start fast, stay out of the way, and never ask you to log in.
  </p>

</BlogPost>
